{"type":"message","id":"4c8810de","parentId":"0185bcda","timestamp":"2026-02-19T19:03:30.327Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Reviewing the Project's Scope**\n\nI'm currently focused on the DMarket Bot project and my role as a subagent. I'm starting by diving into the roadmap documentation, specifically looking at Phase 5 and 6, to get a clear picture of unfinished tasks. The first step will be to familiarize myself with the API circuit breaker's current implementation to understand the state of this component.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771527810204_84","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"docs/ROADMAP_V7.md"},"thoughtSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771527810321_85","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py"}}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":4755,"output":287,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":5042,"cost":{"input":0.00951,"output":0.003444,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.012954}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771527784145}}
{"type":"message","id":"4fcc6b7a","parentId":"4c8810de","timestamp":"2026-02-19T19:03:30.349Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771527810204_84","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# ROADMAP V7.0: COGNITIVE REVOLUTION & HFT SUPREMACY\n\n## Phase 4: Cognitive Architecture (The Brain & MoE)\n- [x] Thinking Mode (Chain-of-Thought)\n- [x] Mixture of Experts (MoE) - Gemini Family Strategy\n- [x] Identity & Knowledge\n\n## Phase 5: HFT Supremacy (The Muscle)\n### 1. Rust Network Layer\n*   **Migration:** Move `aiohttp` logic to Rust using `reqwest` + `tokio`.\n*   **Benefit:** Zero-GC networking, true multithreading, <5ms latency globally.\n\n### 2. TUI Dashboard (Ratatui)\n*   **Tool:** Build a CLI dashboard in Rust (`ratatui` crate).\n\n### 3. Order Book Prediction (ML/Rust)\n*   **Algo:** Implement a lightweight Order Book Imbalance (OBI) predictor in Rust.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 6: Infrastructure, Security & Automation (The Fortress)\n*   [ ] Automated Councils\n*   [ ] Resilience & Defense\n\n---\n\n## MANIFESTO\n> \"Я обязуюсь думать перед каждым вызовом инструмента. Ошибка `dir not found` больше невозможна, так как я сначала проверю `os.name` в блоке размышления. Мой код — это продолжение моей мысли.\"\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771527810348}}
{"type":"message","id":"3ad54474","parentId":"4fcc6b7a","timestamp":"2026-02-19T19:03:30.353Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771527810321_85","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import asyncio\nimport time\nimport functools\nfrom typing import Callable, Any\n\nclass CircuitBreakerOpen(Exception):\n    pass\n\ndef call_with_circuit_breaker(func, *args, **kwargs):\n    # Simplified async circuit breaker logic for MVP\n    # In production, this would track failure counts in a shared state (e.g. Redis)\n    return func(*args, **kwargs)\n\n# For now, just a placeholder decorator if needed\ndef circuit_breaker(failure_threshold: int = 3, recovery_timeout: int = 60):\n    def decorator(func: Callable) -> Callable:\n        @functools.wraps(func)\n        async def wrapper(*args, **kwargs) -> Any:\n            return await func(*args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771527810352}}
{"type":"message","id":"608c2137","parentId":"3ad54474","timestamp":"2026-02-19T19:03:55.032Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Assessing the Circuit Breaker**\n\nI've been reviewing the documentation, specifically the roadmap, to understand the broader context. Phase 5, \"HFT Supremacy,\" highlights the network aspect with \"Rust Network\". This is valuable context, and I'll keep this in mind as I delve into the `api_circuit_breaker.py` code.\n\n\n**Mapping the Dependencies**\n\nI've taken a close look at the roadmap, focusing on Phases 5 and 6. It's clear that the Rust Network Layer will be crucial, potentially impacting how I approach the `api_circuit_breaker.py` implementation. The current stub reinforces the need for a state machine to manage the circuit's lifecycle: closed, open, and half-open states. I will design the error handling to gracefully respect `Retry-After` headers.\n\n\n**Implementing the CircuitBreaker**\n\nOkay, I've reviewed the project's roadmap, focusing on Phase 5's Rust Network layer and Phase 6's infrastructure elements. The `api_circuit_breaker.py` is a stub, so I'm implementing a class-based state machine, handling closed, open, and half-open states. I'm focusing on handling 429 responses correctly using Retry-After, and ensuring thread-safety using asyncio.Lock, and I'll default gracefully if environment variables are not set. The code is ready to start now.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771527835030_86","name":"write","arguments":{"file_path":"src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py","content":"import time\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\nfrom functools import wraps\nfrom typing import Optional, Callable, Any\n\n# Configure logger (ensure it doesn't crash if logging isn't set up elsewhere)\nlogger = logging.getLogger(\"dmarket_bot.circuit_breaker\")\n\nclass CircuitBreakerOpen(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Raised when the circuit breaker is open and refusing requests.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, reset_time: float):\n        self.reset_time = reset_time\n        remaining = max(0, reset_time - time.time())\n        super().__init__(f\"Circuit Breaker is OPEN. Retry in {remaining:.2f}s\")\n\nclass CircuitBreaker:\n    \"\"\"\n    Manages the state of the connection to an external service.\n    States:\n        - CLOSED: Normal operation. Requests flow through.\n        - OPEN:  Requests are blocked immediately. Happens after failure_threshold is reached.\n        - HALF-OPEN: After recovery_timeout, one request is allowed to test the connection.\n    \"\"\"\n    STATE_CLOSED = \"CLOSED\"\n    STATE_OPEN = \"OPEN\"\n    STATE_HALF_OPEN = \"HALF_OPEN\"\n\n    def __init__(self, failure_threshold: int = 5, recovery_timeout: int = 60):\n        self.failure_threshold = failure_threshold\n        self.recovery_timeout = recovery_timeout\n        \n        self._state = self.STATE_CLOSED\n        self._failure_count = 0\n        self._last_failure_time = 0.0\n        self._open_until = 0.0\n        \n        # Lock to ensure thread/task safety during state transitions\n        self._lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\n    @property\n    def state(self):\n        return self._state\n\n    async def call(self, func: Callable, *args, **kwargs) -> Any:\n        \"\"\"\n        Executes the async function wrapped with circuit breaker logic.\n        \"\"\"\n        async with self._lock:\n            if self._state == self.STATE_OPEN:\n                if time.time() >= self._open_until:\n                    logger.info(\"Circuit Breaker entering HALF-OPEN state.\")\n                    self._state = self.STATE_HALF_OPEN\n                else:\n                    raise CircuitBreakerOpen(self._open_until)\n\n            if self._state == self.STATE_HALF_OPEN:\n                # In half-open, we allow this call to proceed. \n                # If it succeeds, we reset. If it fails, we go back to Open.\n                pass\n\n        try:\n            result = await func(*args, **kwargs)\n            \n            # Successful call\n            if self._state != self.STATE_CLOSED:\n                await self._reset()\n            return result\n\n        except Exception as e:\n            await self._record_failure(e)\n            raise\n\n    async def _reset(self):\n        async with self._lock:\n            if self._state != self.STATE_CLOSED:\n                logger.info(\"Circuit Breaker recovered. Resetting to CLOSED.\")\n                self._state = self.STATE_CLOSED\n                self._failure_count = 0\n                self._open_until = 0.0\n\n    async def _record_failure(self, error: Exception):\n        async with self._lock:\n            self._failure_count += 1\n            self._last_failure_time = time.time()\n            \n            # Check for 429 Retry-After specific handling\n            # Assuming error object might have 'status' or response attribute with headers\n            retry_after = self._parse_retry_after(error)\n            \n            if retry_after:\n                logger.warning(f\"429 Detected. Circuit Breaker opening for {retry_after}s.\")\n                self._state = self.STATE_OPEN\n                self._open_until = time.time() + retry_after\n                return\n\n            if self._state == self.STATE_HALF_OPEN or self._failure_count >= self.failure_threshold:\n                if self._state != self.STATE_OPEN:\n                    logger.warning(f\"Circuit Breaker OPENING due to {self._failure_count} failures.\")\n                    self._state = self.STATE_OPEN\n                    self._open_until = time.time() + self.recovery_timeout\n\n    def _parse_retry_after(self, error: Exception) -> Optional[int]:\n        \"\"\"\n        Attempts to extract Retry-After header from an exception.\n        Supports common aiohttp ClientResponseError or similar structures.\n        \"\"\"\n        try:\n            # Check if error has a 'headers' attribute (aiohttp)\n            headers = getattr(error, 'headers', None)\n            if not headers and hasattr(error, 'response'):\n                 headers = getattr(error.response, 'headers', None)\n\n            if headers:\n                retry_val = headers.get(\"Retry-After\") or headers.get(\"retry-after\")\n                if retry_val:\n                    return int(retry_val)\n            \n            # Check if it's a 429 status without headers, use default backoff\n            status = getattr(error, 'status', None)\n            if status == 429:\n                return self.recovery_timeout  # Default to recovery timeout if no header\n\n        except (ValueError, AttributeError):\n            pass\n        return None\n\n# Global instance or factory can be used.\n# For simple usage, we provide a decorator.\n\ndef circuit_breaker_decorator(failure_threshold: int = 3, recovery_timeout: int = 60):\n    # Create a separate breaker instance for each decorated function to avoid sharing state \n    # between unrelated endpoints unless intended. \n    # *Note*: In a real bot, you might want a singleton breaker per *API Domain* (e.g., one for all DMarket calls).\n    # Here we instantiate one per decorated function for simplicity, or we could accept a shared breaker.\n    \n    cb = CircuitBreaker(failure_threshold, recovery_timeout)\n\n    def decorator(func: Callable) -> Callable:\n        @wraps(func)\n        async def wrapper(*args, **kwargs) -> Any:\n            return await cb.call(func, *args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":5389,"output":1987,"cacheRead":4608,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7376,"cost":{"input":0.010778,"output":0.023844,"cacheRead":0.0009216000000000001,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0355436}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771527810354}}
